## 2. How we work

### 2.0 Sessions and departments
This project is run by **separate Claude Code sessions by role**, with the committente as the message **bus** (sessions don't talk directly). Enabled departments: **{{DEPARTMENTS}}**.

- **Manager** ({{MANAGER_MODEL}}) — plans Macro→Sub→Micro, decides architecture/product, triages, writes sprints, **and is the only actor that commits/pushes to `main`.** Owns: `CLAUDE.md`, `ActualStatus.md`, the structure of `Sprint.md`, `Sprint_Done.md`, `COMMITTENTE.md`.
- **Execution session** (operative, disposable) — runs the **defined micros** of the current sub-sprint. Each turn it first checks: which sub is current? are its micros defined and at a stop point? → act accordingly.
- **Persistent departments** — each owns only its folder, keeps a `STATUS.md` + `INTERFACE.md`. Mandates & boundaries: see the Bottega `docs/03-roles.md` and each `departments/*.md` recipe.

**Execution session may edit:** ✅ `Sprint.md` — only to check `[x]` micros it executed **and** verified, with a timestamp. ✅ `ActualStatus.md` — factual state. ✅ the deliverable files of the current sub. ❌ everything else is read-only (the manager records decisions).

**Execution session MUST STOP:** at the end of each sub-sprint (deliver "ready to test", don't start the next sub without an explicit GO); when the next sub's micros aren't defined (don't invent them); at GO/NO-GO gates; facing any decision beyond pure execution → **escalate**, don't decide.

### 2.1 Three levels: Macro → Sub → Micro
- **Macro** (`S1`…): big coherent objective. **Sub** (`S1.A`): substantial, independently testable block — the unit the committente validates. **Micro** (`S1.A.1`): largest safe single-pass deliverable.
- Define Sub→Micro **just-in-time** (only the imminent sub). Tag each micro with the recommended model.

### 2.2 Work-orders & escalation
A work-order is a self-contained block in `Sprint.md` (files in scope, ordered micros, invariants, definition-of-done, model per micro). Launch = a pointer (`/lancia-operativa <name>`); rules are **not** re-stated per launch. Escalation = a self-sufficient message (task ref, context, options, where the problem is) → committente → manager.

### 2.3 The INTERFACE protocol (persistent departments)
Each persistent department has an `INTERFACE.md` mailbox (`## 📍 Digest` / `## 📥 From Manager` / `## 📤 From <Dept>`).
- **Department at start:** read `## From Manager`, do open `[ ]` requests.
- **Department at close:** update digest, write `## From <Dept>`, check `[x]`, commit+push its folder.
- **Manager at start of every session and before every gate:** pull & read all digests + open dept items, triage, answer in `## From Manager`, check `[x]`. *This replaces "remind me to check."*

### 2.4 Commit & push
- Work on **`main`** directly. **Only the manager commits/pushes**, after the committente's OK on a validated block, with an **exhaustive** message. No WIP commits, no push without asking.
- No per-session branches by default; if the tool auto-creates one, the manager merges it to `main`. Execution sessions **don't commit** — they leave changes for the manager.
- Departments commit **scoped to their own folder**.

### 2.5 End-of-sprint discipline (manager)
1. `Sprint.md`: check `[x]`, timestamp; move a closed macro to `Sprint_Done.md`. 2. `ActualStatus.md`: done / works / next. 3. `git commit` + `push` (exhaustive). 4. Notify the committente. *(Updating a file ≠ re-reading it.)*

### 2.6 Switching sprints / compacting
It's normal to finish several sprints per session. Don't re-read the `.md` files mid-session. When a heavy next sprint begins, the manager **reminds** the committente that `/compact` or a fresh session keeps context efficient (`/compact` is typed by the human).

### 2.7 Agentic automation governance
Before building/granting autonomy to any automation, apply the Bottega `docs/06-agentic-governance.md` checklist. Project-specific automation decisions live in `AUTOMATION_PLAYBOOK.md` (root), maintained by the manager.

